<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="227" pageId="13" pageNumber="226" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[826,1441,1728,1903]" lastBlockId="14.[144,759,198,801]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="227" pageId="13" pageNumber="226">
<emphasis box="[826,972,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="226">Distribution:</emphasis>
The original distribution of 
<emphasis box="[1309,1441,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="226">
C. a. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Osgood" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[1374,1441,1728,1749]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="13" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="siccus">siccus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was Cerralvo Island (geographical group 29), which is close to the south-eastern coast of the peninsula. However, specimens of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Merriam" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[1145,1290,1820,1841]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="13" pageNumber="226" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arenarius">
<emphasis box="[1145,1290,1820,1841]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="226">C. arenarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex collected in the Los Planes Basin (geographical group 31) are genetically similar to the Cerralvo Island population. Los Planes Basin is surrounded by mountain ranges on three sides and opens to the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[144,259,259,281]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">California</collectingRegion>
facing Cerralvo Island, which is 
<quantity box="[651,720,259,281]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" unit="km" value="11.0">11 km</quantity>
off the coast (
<bibRefCitation author="Gastil G &amp; Minch J &amp; Phillips RP" box="[267,629,290,312]" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" pagination="13 - 25" refId="ref10879" refString="Gastil G, Minch J, Phillips RP. 1983. The geology and ages of the island. In: Case TJ, Cody ML, eds. Island biogeography in the Mar de Cortez. Berkeley: University of California Press, 13 - 25." type="book chapter" year="1983">Gastil, Minch &amp; Phillips, 1983</bibRefCitation>
). The relatively high ridges isolate the population from other species in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Merriam" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[309,452,351,372]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arenarius">
<emphasis box="[309,452,351,372]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">C. arenarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Roth" baseAuthorityYear="1976" box="[569,707,351,372]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dalquesti">
<emphasis box="[569,707,351,372]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">C. dalquesti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Merriam" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[144,288,382,403]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arenarius">
<emphasis box="[144,288,382,403]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">C. arenarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[144,759,198,801]" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis box="[168,287,413,434]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Following 
<bibRefCitation author="Osgood WH" box="[428,599,412,434]" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" pagination="19 - 22" refId="ref11239" refString="Osgood WH. 1907. Four new pocket mice. Proceeding of the Biological Society of Washington 20: 19 - 22." type="journal article" year="1907">Osgood (1907)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Osgood" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[618,725,412,434]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="siccus">
<emphasis box="[618,725,412,434]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">C. siccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Merriam" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[280,432,443,464]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arenarius">
<emphasis box="[280,432,443,464]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">C. arenarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; however, externally it is decidedly larger than 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Merriam" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[395,537,474,495]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arenarius">
<emphasis box="[395,537,474,495]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">C. arenarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with very weak or rarely present rump bristles. The skull is decidedly larger and heavier; the mastoids are somewhat larger and have broad ascending branches of the supraoccipital ridge.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[144,759,198,801]" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis box="[168,421,626,648]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">Subspecific taxonomy:</emphasis>
No genetic or morphological differences were found amongst the specimens from the basin and the island. The evidence does not support the designation of any subspecies as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Osgood" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[654,752,718,740]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="siccus">
<emphasis box="[654,752,718,740]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">C. siccus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[144,759,198,801]" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis box="[168,294,749,770]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">Comments:</emphasis>
<materialsCitation location="Cerralvo Island" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" specimenCount="1">
The 
<specimenCount box="[382,562,749,771]" pageId="14" pageNumber="227" type="generic">five specimens</specimenCount>
from 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03C62313FFEEFFA5FC16F921B4193C26:8EB0C4DEFFEDFFA5FD74FD56B6CC3C26" name="Cerralvo Island" pageId="14" pageNumber="227">Cerralvo Island</location>
have the same haplotype
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
